I have identified a workflow that can be used to generate phylogenetic trees that treat gaps as indels. The workflow uses two tools: gappy and IQTree. 

1. Run your alignment through gappy (GitHub: https://github.com/alexdonath/gappy2).  Gappy identifies potentially relevant gaps and produces a PHYLIP‑formatted file that can be fed into most tree‑building programs.  Gappy accounts for indels, but not substitutions, so the output will need to be combined with another analysis to generate the tree you want.

2. IQTree can perform a partitioned analysis of mixed data.  Create a NEXUS file that defines two partitions: one for the original alignment and one for the gappy output.  For example:

   #nexus
   begin sets;
   charset part1 = alignment.fasta: *;
   charset part2 = GAPPY2_alignment.fasta_2-inf.phy: *;
   end;

3. Run IQTree with the NEXUS file:

   iqtree -p example.nex

The resulting tree will be generated using both substitutions (from the original alignment) and indels (from the gappy output).  In a small test case (a single MSA example from a public database), the tree was identical to the tree produced by running only the original alignment through IQTree.  This indicates that more thorough testing is required, but the workflow provides a solid baseline that can be refined with future updates.

Let me know if you see any glaring flaws in this logic; I may provide edits in the future if significant tweaks or overhauls are made.

For metadata, I would use a SQL schema something like the following:

CREATE TABLE Project (
  ac TEXT, -- project/Study accession
  PRIMARY KEY (ac)
);

CREATE TABLE Sample (
  -- biological sample/biopsy
  ac TEXT,
  PRIMARY KEY (ac)
);

CREATE TABLE AnalysisSample (
  prj_ac TEXT, -- project accession (Project.ac)
  symbol TEXT, -- a short name unique in the project
  sample_ac TEXT, -- sample accession (Sample.ac)
  PRIMARY KEY (prj_ac, symbol)
);

CREATE TABLE Collection (
  -- a BAM file
  ac TEXT, -- collection/alignment file accession
  prj_ac TEXT, -- project accession (Project.ac)
  PRIMARY KEY (ac)
);

CREATE TABLE ReadGroup (
  cl_ac TEXT, -- collection accession (Collection.ac)
  rg_id TEXT, -- @RG-ID
  sample_sym TEXT, -- @RG-SM; matching AnalysisSample.symbol
  PRIMARY KEY (cl_ac, rg_id)
);

CREATE TABLE VariantSet (
  -- a VCF file
  ac TEXT, -- VCF file accession
  prj_ac TEXT, -- project accession (Project.ac)
  PRIMARY KEY (ac)
);

CREATE TABLE VariantSample (
  vs_ac TEXT, -- VCF file accession (VariantSet.ac)
  sample_sym TEXT, -- sample symbol in the VCF file; matching AnalysisSample.symbol
  PRIMARY KEY (vs_ac, sample_sym)
);

In the schema, you have Project and biological Sample tables, which are independent of each other at the high level. An AnalysisSample describes a sample used in BAM or VCF and connects Project and biological Sample. Importantly, each AnalysisSample has a symbol unique in a project (see the primary index). This is the symbol on a BAM read group line or on a VCF sample line. A Collection is in effect a BAM/CRAM file. In theory, a BAM file may contain more than one sample (though rare in practice), which is addressed by a separate ReadGroup table. Finally, a VariantSet is a VCF file. VariantSample tells you which samples are included in each VCF file.

This is the skeleton of a full schema. You can add extra fields to appropriate tables (e.g. file path and hg19/hg38/etc to Collection, read length to ReadGroup and family ID to Sample). You also need indices for efficient table joining and perhaps more tables for complex structures (e.g. pedigree).

For the projects I have participated, this schema should work most of time. It is inspired by GA4GH's JSON schema, but my version is in SQL, is simpler and also has a slightly different structure which I think is better.

